LAGOS – The need to engage local professionals in the handling of Federal and state government major contract jobs has been again reiterated even as major contract jobs continue to elude indigenous professionals. A facility maintenance expert Engineer Sofolabi Adedeji dropped the hint, in an interview with Daily Independent. According to him, in the last two decades, most high profile construction jobs have been given by both the Federal and state government to foreign construction firms to the detriment of local and indigenous professionals. Expunge Governor’s Assent To Land Titles In Land Use… Building Collapse: LASBCA Overwhelmed By Numerous Construction… His words:” It is indeed disheartening that our government both at state and Federal levels has deemed it improper, to award major contract jobs to local professionals who have core competence in their area of specialisation. Instead, they have continued to patronise ‘half-baked foreign professionals who at best, could be descried as artisans More worrisome, is that when these so-called foreign professionals arrive the shores of this country, their Nigerian counterparts are made to undergo some for of training under them(the so-called foreign experts) who are not better than the local professionals. Adedeji, who is a Fellow of the Nigerian Society of Engineers(NSE) wondered why in this age and time when the Federal Government should be encouraging local professionals, they are being subjected to a ‘second slavery’ by way of making them serve under people that they are far more intelligent than. According to him, this type of mindset would never engender development, rather it would continue to make our brilliant minds lravevtge country in droves.